<DOC><DOCNO> AP900210-0117 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-90 1720EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Niger 1stLd-Writethru   02-10 0282</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Niger, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0523,0288</SECOND><HEAD>Three Reported Killed in Student Unrest in Niger</HEAD><NOTE>EDS: Leads with 4 grafs to correct that news agency reportingthree dead Saturday. Pickup 5th pvs, `Police first...</NOTE><DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hundreds of students staging ananti-government protest clashed with police in the Niger capital,and official reports Saturday said three people died.   The military Cabinet of President Ali Saibou convened inemergency session Saturday to discuss the student unrest.   The French news agency Agence France-Presse initially said fiveto 10 students may have died in the confrontation Friday in Niamey.On Saturday, the Niger News Agency and AFP said police shot andkilled three people and wounded 33.   AFP quoted witnesses as saying about 100 armed police were sentto block a bridge between the University of Niamey and thecapital's center to stop protesting university and secondary schoolstudents from reaching offices of government ministries.   Police first fired tear gas at demonstrators and then chargedthe crowd several times. Some of them fired into the crowd, theagency quoted witnesses as saying.   The university has been closed since Thursday, when hundreds ofstudents started rallying to protest a government freeze on hiringcivil servants, including university graduates.   Government officials have said the students expect too much fromthis north-central African country that is among the poorest in theworld.   Students also have been demanding an end to alleged corruptionin the government of Saibou, a brigadier general who was at adrought conference in neighboring Bissau during the confrontation.   Niger News Agency said Saibou returned home later Friday and wasmeeting Saturday with his advisers and other politicians in aneffort to end the unrest.</TEXT></DOC>